---- SYNCHRONIZATION ----

>> B7: The "exec" system call returns -1 if loading the new executable
>> fails, so it cannot return before the new executable has completed
>> loading.  How does your code ensure this?  How is the load
>> success/failure status passed back to the thread that calls "exec"?

When the exec system call is called, the exec handler calls process_execute()
on the new file. When the new thread for the exec process is created, its added
as a child thread of the current running thread. The child thread struct
contains a "load_sema" sempahore which is initalized to one. Back in exec handler, 
the current running thread calls sema_down on "child->load_sema" which forces the
current running thread to wait until the child thread calls sema_up on its "load_sema".
The child thread calls sema up its load_sema once the file has been loaded in
start_process. This is how we make sure that the current thread does not 
return until the exec has finished loading.

The load success/failure status passed back to the thread that calls "exec" 
by reading the success boolean member of the childs threads' struct. The success
boolean member is updated in the start_process once the new exec file has finished 
loading.


